passages.text: Insights into Casinos, Airlines, Duty Free, Hainan, Hotels, OTA & the Rise of Leisure

After the strong GGR data in June/July, market expectations have generally been lifted. The latest GGR in Aug maintained its strong momentum \(+12\%\) yoy or tracking at \(91\%\) of pre- COVID19 levels (vs. \(19\%\) yoy or \(88\% /90\%\) in Jun/July), even against a relatively high base in Aug last year ( \(81\%\) of pre- COVID19 level vs. \(74 - 76\%\) in Jun/July). August also set another new record high post the pandemic with MOP715mn daily run- rate (vs. MOP702/714mn in Jun/Jul). Ytd, GGR has grown \(+7\%\) yoy. We attribute the continued strength to (1) robust inbound visitation at \(\sim 136k\) per day in Aug, \(+16\%\) yoy (vs. \(+14\%\) in Jul) or exceeding FY19 level by \(\sim 17\%\) (vs. \(- 2\%\) in Jul); and (2) busy event schedule and high- profile singer concerts, e.g., Eason Chan on Aug 1- 10th and Tencent Music Event at Galaxy Arena on Aug 22- 24; Exhibit 15).

Assuming VIP GGR at \(30 - 40\%\) of the pre- pandemic level, we estimate mass- market GGR has recovered to \(\sim 125 - 130\%\) . Based on latest monthly data by Statistic Department, which usually lag by a month, Macau's \(+14\%\) yoy increase in inbound visitation was led by mainland Chinese travelers (+17% yoy to 2.6mn), followed by foreigners (+8% yoy to 0.3mn) and HK residents (+6% yoy to 0.6mn). Continuing the trend in prior months, more visitors came from nearby Guangdong province (+28% yoy) while those from Shanghai/Hunan slipped slightly by \(- 5\% / - 3\%\) respectively.

Looking ahead, as discussed in our prior reports (Jun 2), the base could become slightly more favorable in Sept- Dec when the industry was affected by the criminalization of illegal money exchanges taking effect from Oct- 2024 and President Xi's visit the 25th anniversary of Macau's handover back to China in Dec- 2024 (Nov 2024). With an 8- day long holidays during the upcoming Golden Week and the 15th National Games co- hosted by Guangdong, HK and Macau in mid- Nov, Macau's visitation and GGR could see continued support. Assuming Macau's GGR tracks at \(\sim 90\%\) or \(+14\%\) yoy in Sept- Dec, we now

forecast \(+9\%\) yoy FY25 GGR growth to MOP248bn or US\(30.9bn (vs. +7\%\) previously), followed by \(+7\%\) yoy in FY26E. Exhibit 1 lists our FY25E GGR growth forecast based on different growth rate for the rest of the year. Factoring in our latest market share and cost assumptions, we adjust our FY25- 27E EBITDA estimates for covered casino operators by \(- 3\%\) to \(+10\%\) . Rolling over to FY26E, we revise our 12- month target prices by \(+6\%\) to \(68\%\) based on unchanged multiples. Our EBITDA forecasts are \(6 - 8\%\) above Bloomberg consensus estimates over the next 1- 2 years (see Exhibit 2 - Exhibit 4 for more details).

Wrapping up their 2Q25 results (Sands, Galaxy, MGM, Wynn, MLCO, SJM), most operators' came inline with our expectations except for SJM which was below due to lower VIP win rate and negative operating leverage. Investors remain divided about SJM's execution on its announced acquisitions (i.e., Ponte 16, L'Arc casinos, additional space at Old Lisboa) in helping it to retain the \(5\%\) GGR market share originally captured by its satellite casinos, which will be closed by year- end. Key highlights include: (1) Industry mass/slot GGR ended up \(+6\%\) qoq vs. VIP rolling flat qoq (Exhibit 16), suggesting the accelerated market growth has clearly been driven by mass- market, incrementally from more middle/grand mass players, instead of VIP as some brokers/consultants suggested; (2) Despite concerns that Sands China would offer more cash rebates, industry competition was not as intense as feared with promotional allowance as \(0\%\) of GGR for the industry only edging up by \(+0.4\) pts qoq to \(18.2\%\) in 2Q25. EBITDA grew \(+4\%\) qoq and margin only slipped by - 0.2pts qoq to \(27.2\%\) . Several premium- mass focused properties actually saw promotional allowance \(0\%\) dropped qoq, i.e., City of Dreams, Wynn Palace (Exhibit 17); (3) Regarding shareholder returns, Galaxy surprised positively by raising its earnings payout from \(50\%\) to \(58\%\) . MGM China also maintained its payout unchanged at \(- 50\%\) . Although Sands China did not lift its DPS or payout at the interim, we would not be surprised if it did so for its final DPS. In terms of latest market share trend in 3Q25 qtd, we gather from our channel checks that Wynn's share has bounced back to \(13 - 14\%\) (vs. \(12\%\) in 2Q25) after revamping its loyalty program in June, while SJM's slipped to below \(12\%\) in Aug, dragged by underperformance of satellite casinos (Exhibit 9). Investors generally expect Sands China to deliver better market share during the summer season.

Since we published our big sector update note in early- Jul (Jul 2), share prices of our covered Macau gaming names have surged sharply by an average of \(40 - 50\%\) over the past 2- 3 months. Expectations have certainly been lifted, but in our view valuations still do not look demanding — especially rolling out to FY26E when sector average EV/EBITDA and FCF yield are still hovering at 9x or \(7 - 8\%\) respectively. Sands China (Buy- rated) remains our preferred pick as we see the market remains divided on its ability to regain GGR market share. Should market recovery continue to be led by mass- market, the group should be able to benefit more given its spare hotel rooms and non- gaming amenities. Meanwhile, we think it could be the next operator raising DPS. We also like Buy- rated Galaxy for potential (albeit more gradual) GGR market share upside from further ramp- up of Capella hotel. Galaxy is the only operator with noticeable capacity growth from new project launches looking out over 1- 2 years' time (i.e., Galaxy Macau Phase 4). MGM China's valuation remains the most undemanding across all six operators trading at 7.3x FY26E EV/EBITDA, 9.5x P/E and offers \(5.3\%\) dividend yield
based on our assumption that it can contain 15- 16% GGR market share, potentially capturing gaming volume from the adjacent satellite casinos in Peninsula to be closed by end- FY25.

Investment Thesis - SJM HoldingsSJM is one of six Macau based casino operators. We are Neutral rated as a relative call, considering (1) Grand Lisboa Palace (GLP) ramp up is losing steam as the low hanging fruit from new initiatives have been picked; (2) Increased competition on the Peninsula; and (3) Acquiring the 2 satellite casinos could further leverage SJM's stretched balance sheet and delay its dividend resumption. Valuation looks fair compared to industry peers on EV/EBITDA.

Investment Thesis - MGM ChinaMGM China is one of six Macau based casino operators. We are Buy rated for a few reasons: (1) Success in maintaining mid- teens % GGR market share despite increased competition from adjacent properties; (2) Less pressure for incremental step- up in capital commitment spending ahead; (3) Potential upside from gaining GGR share in the Peninsula from gaming volume originally captured by satellite casinos set to close; and (4) Undemanding valuation on various measures, and scope for potential upside from Thailand IR if approved.

Investment Thesis - Wynn MacauWynn Macau is one of six Macau based casino operators. We are Neutral rated on the stock as a relative call within our Macau coverage universe, with the stock trading broadly in line with the sector average. We expect its GGR market share trend to normalize ahead in view of rising competition from adjacent new hotel launches (e.g., Londoner Grand suites by Sands China, Capella by Galaxy). Key risks are (1) better/worse- than- expected GGR; and (2) more/less intense competition from other Macau operators.

MLCO is one of six Macau based casino operators. We are Buy rated on the stock as we believe the company is well positioned to capture more GGR market share ahead with the opening of Studio City Phase 2. At the current price, the stock's valuation looks undemanding on EV to run- rate annualized EBITDA, trading at a discount to the sector average. Key downside risks are (1) worse- than- expected GGR recovery trends; (2) competition in the Philippines from newly opened casinos; and (3) ADR potential delisting risks.

Galaxy is one of six Macau based casino operators. We are Buy rated on the stock for following reasons: (1) we believe it is positioned to better capture the market upcycle ahead via its proven stronger execution and more resilient performance; (2) step- up in hotel room capacity expansion to drive share gain in the medium term. Stronger track record from past openings; (3) better transition to EBITDA and FCF for cost discipline and less geared balance sheet; and (4) the stock appears to be not pricing in much upside from future capacity expansion. Key risks are (1) worse- than- expected GGR trends (e.g., lower Chinese visitation, tighter capital controls); and (2) intense competition from other Macau operators if GGR softens significantly.

Investment Thesis - Sands ChinaSands China is one of six Macau based casino operators. We are Buy rated on the stock for several reasons: (1) We believe it is a beneficiary of grind mass GGR growth ahead; (2) Completion of the Londoner revamp should strengthen its competitiveness and better utilize Sands Cotai Central; and (3) Valuation is not demanding when compared to its historical average. Key risks are (1) worse- than- expected GGR trends, e.g., lower mainland Chinese visitation and tighter capital controls as these would have a negative impact on gaming demand; and (2) higher- than- expected cannibalization from its newly opened properties following the rebranding of Sands Cotai Central.

Melco International Development is a multinational investment holding company based in Central, Hong Kong. The company invests in the casino and hospitality business and other businesses in Hong Kong, Macau, the Philippines, and Cyprus. We are Neutral rated considering (1) valuation is no longer attractive after its outperformance vs. listed subsidiary MLCO, compared to historical average of \(\sim 30\%\) NAV discount; (2) MLCO's GGR market share has not shown much improvement months even post management reshuffling; and (3) FCF generation affected by higher capex and borrowing costs. Key risks include (1) Better/worse- than- expected GGR share trend; (2) Better/worse- than- expected competition environment; (3) Movement of CNY against USD.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
